'''Marion Frances Chevalier''' (January 21, 1902 &ndash; February 17, 1990)<ref>Birth date from [http://cat.opal-libraries.org:2082/search?/aChevalley%2C+J./achevalley+j/-27%2C0%2C0%2CB/frameset&FF=achevalier+marion+frances+1902&1%2C1%2C Ohio Private Academic Libraries catalog entry].</ref> was a [[philology|philologist]] best known for her discovery in the Bibliothèque d'Orléans of ''The Adventures and Marriage of Panurge'', a play by [[Pousset de Montauban]] that had remained unknown for 250 years and was the first drama derived from the works of [[Rabelais]].<ref>{{citation|last=Chevalier|first=Marion F.|title=A Dramatic Adaptation of Rabelais in the Seventeenth Century: Les Aventures et Le Mariage de Panurge (1674) by Pousset de Montauban, with a Study of his Life and Other Plays|year=1933|publisher=Johns Hopkins University}}.  Review by C. D. Zdanowicz (1934), ''[[Modern Language Notes]]'' '''49'''(7): 483–484.  Review by Robert V. Merrill (1934), ''[[Modern Philology]]'' '''32'''(1): 97.  Review by F. J. Tanquerey (1935, in French), ''[[Modern Language Review]]''  '''30'''(2): 250–251.</ref> Her analysis of this play formed the basis of her Ph.D. thesis, in 1933, from [[Johns Hopkins University]], under the supervision of [[Henry Carrington Lancaster]]. She is the namesake of a professorship in French and [[Comparative Literature]] at the [[University of Southern California]], currently held by [[Peggy Kamuf]].<ref>[http://www.usc.edu/schools/college/engl/people/faculty1003397.html USC College Department of English<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> A photograph of her can be found in the Johns Hopkins University Historical Photograph Collection.<ref>[http://www.library.jhu.edu/collections/specialcollections/archives/photo_subjects.html Historical Photo Collection subject listing].</ref>

